TY  - JOUR
T1  - Welfare‐Improving Asymmetric Information in Dynamic Insurance Markets
AU  - de Garidel‐Thoron, Thomas
Y1  - 2005/02/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/426039
DO  - 10.1086/426039
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 121
EP  - 150
VL  - 113
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This article presents a two?period asymmetric learning model of insurance markets. When information about past accidents is not shared by insurers, asymmetries of information develop through time. Equilibrium contracts exist, are payoff unique, and display a realistic bonus?malus pattern. Eliminating asymmetries through information sharing is welfare decreasing, in contrast with past contributions on insurance and adverse selection. When second?period contract offers cannot be contingent on initial contract choice, a strict increase in welfare is obtained through menus of contracts, although initial contract choice is in itself worthless information.
AB  - This article presents a two?period asymmetric learning model of insurance markets. When information about past accidents is not shared by insurers, asymmetries of information develop through time. Equilibrium contracts exist, are payoff unique, and display a realistic bonus?malus pattern. Eliminating asymmetries through information sharing is welfare decreasing, in contrast with past contributions on insurance and adverse selection. When second?period contract offers cannot be contingent on initial contract choice, a strict increase in welfare is obtained through menus of contracts, although initial contract choice is in itself worthless information.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/426039
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/426039
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Selection on Observed and Unobserved Variables: Assessing the Effectiveness of Catholic Schools
AU  - Altonji, Joseph G.
AU  - Elder, Todd E.
AU  - Taber, Christopher R.
Y1  - 2005/02/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/426036
DO  - 10.1086/426036
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 151
EP  - 184
VL  - 113
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper we measure the effect of Catholic high school attendance on educational attainment and test scores. Because we do not have a good instrumental variable for Catholic school attendance, we develop new estimation methods based on the idea that the amount of selection on the observed explanatory variables in a model provides a guide to the amount of selection on the unobservables. We also propose an informal way to assess selectivity bias based on measuring the ratio of selection on unobservables to selection on observables that would be required if one is to attribute the entire effect of Catholic school attendance to selection bias. We use our methods to estimate the effect of attending a Catholic high school on a variety of outcomes. Our main conclusion is that Catholic high schools substantially increase the probability of graduating from high school and, more tentatively, attending college. We find little evidence of an effect on test scores.
AB  - In this paper we measure the effect of Catholic high school attendance on educational attainment and test scores. Because we do not have a good instrumental variable for Catholic school attendance, we develop new estimation methods based on the idea that the amount of selection on the observed explanatory variables in a model provides a guide to the amount of selection on the unobservables. We also propose an informal way to assess selectivity bias based on measuring the ratio of selection on unobservables to selection on observables that would be required if one is to attribute the entire effect of Catholic school attendance to selection bias. We use our methods to estimate the effect of attending a Catholic high school on a variety of outcomes. Our main conclusion is that Catholic high schools substantially increase the probability of graduating from high school and, more tentatively, attending college. We find little evidence of an effect on test scores.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/426036
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/426036
Y2  - 2024/03/22
